<paragraph blockId="95.[189,1399,448,580]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">
<taxonomicName authority="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin, 2018" authorityName="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2018" box="[189,592,448,474]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hauseri" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis box="[189,592,448,474]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Sphegina (Asiosphegina) hauseri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[605,703,448,474]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
resembles those other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meigen" authorityYear="1822" box="[997,1106,448,474]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[997,1106,448,474]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Sphegina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which have a strongly asymmetrical male sternum IV posteriorly armed with many strong black setae, but is easily distinguished by the characters given in the key. Among these species the male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authority="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin, 2018" authorityName="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2018" box="[1091,1259,518,545]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hauseri" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis box="[1091,1259,518,545]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">S. (A.) hauseri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1266,1356,518,544]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are unique in having the curved surstylus expanded on apical half.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
